"Rives J., Rieradevall J., Gabarrell X.","LCA comparison of container systems in municipal solid waste management",2010,"Waste Management","30","6",,"949","957",,,10.1016/j.wasman.2010.01.027,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77951252552&partnerID=40&md5=bfd07074e7116f5457e0f4fa1f3d9ed0","SosteniPrA (UAB-IRTA), Institute of Environmental Science and Technology (ICTA), Universitat Autònoma de Barcelona (UAB), 08193 Bellaterra, Barcelona, Spain; Department of Chemical Engineering, Universitat Autònoma de Barcelona (UAB), 08193 Bellaterra, Barcelona, Spain","Rives, J., SosteniPrA (UAB-IRTA), Institute of Environmental Science and Technology (ICTA), Universitat Autònoma de Barcelona (UAB), 08193 Bellaterra, Barcelona, Spain; Rieradevall, J., SosteniPrA (UAB-IRTA), Institute of Environmental Science and Technology (ICTA), Universitat Autònoma de Barcelona (UAB), 08193 Bellaterra, Barcelona, Spain, Department of Chemical Engineering, Universitat Autònoma de Barcelona (UAB), 08193 Bellaterra, Barcelona, Spain; Gabarrell, X., SosteniPrA (UAB-IRTA), Institute of Environmental Science and Technology (ICTA), Universitat Autònoma de Barcelona (UAB), 08193 Bellaterra, Barcelona, Spain, Department of Chemical Engineering, Universitat Autònoma de Barcelona (UAB), 08193 Bellaterra, Barcelona, Spain","The planning and design of integrated municipal solid waste management (MSWM) systems requires accurate environmental impact evaluation of the systems and their components. This research assessed, quantified and compared the environmental impact of the first stage of the most used MSW container systems. The comparison was based on factors such as the volume of the containers, from small bins of 60-80. l to containers of 2400. l, and on the manufactured materials, steel and high-density polyethylene (HDPE). Also, some parameters such as frequency of collections, waste generation, filling percentage and waste container contents, were established to obtain comparable systems. The methodological framework of the analysis was the life cycle assessment (LCA), and the impact assessment method was based on CML 2 baseline 2000. Results indicated that, for the same volume, the collection systems that use HDPE waste containers had more of an impact than those using steel waste containers, in terms of abiotic depletion, global warming, ozone layer depletion, acidification, eutrophication, photochemical oxidation, human toxicity and terrestrial ecotoxicity. Besides, the collection systems using small HDPE bins (60. l or 80. l) had most impact while systems using big steel containers (2400. l) had less impact. Subsequent sensitivity analysis about the parameters established demonstrated that they could change the ultimate environmental impact of each waste container collection system, but that the comparative relationship between systems was similar. © 2010 Elsevier Ltd.",,"Abiotic depletion; Collection systems; Ecotoxicity; Environmental impact evaluation; Human toxicity; Impact assessments; Life-cycle assessments; Methodological frameworks; Municipal solid waste management; Ozone layer depletion; Photochemical oxidation; Planning and design; Waste containers; Waste generation; Bins; Environmental impact; Eutrophication; Global warming; Life cycle; Ozone; Ozone layer; Planning; Sensitivity analysis; Solid wastes; Toxicity; Waste management; Steel containers; polyethylene; steel; comparative study; environmental impact assessment; life cycle analysis; municipal solid waste; repository; sensitivity analysis; volume; waste management; acidification; article; container; controlled study; ecotoxicity; environmental impact; eutrophication; greenhouse effect; municipal solid waste; ozone depletion; photooxidation; priority journal; sensitivity analysis; solid waste management; Environmental Monitoring; Environmental Pollution; Refuse Disposal",,"polyethylene, 9002-88-4; steel, 12597-69-2",,,,"Aisa, J., Javierre, C., Castany, J., De La Serna, J.A., 